export const batch162 = {
  'rich-routines-simple-habits-that-enrich-every-area-of-your-life.json': {
    base: { id: 'rich-routines-simple-habits-that-enrich-every-area-of-your-life', title: 'Rich Routines', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781682117518 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Learn to pick the right mentors',
        text: 'Steve Houghton once had a strange encounter in a parking lot. A man he had bumped into offered him a piece of advice that stuck. Retire in your twenties to enjoy your youth, the man said, and pick up work when you are older. The fellow seemed proud of his choices, but Steve noticed the worn coat and the empty look. A minute later he remembered the man climbing out of a trash bin.\n\nNever accept guidance from people whose lives you would not want to live.\n\nThat odd meeting pushed Steve to look at his own path. He decided to spend his twenties the way few people would, so that later in life he could live in a way few people can. He began to value small daily progress and built simple routines across every part of his life, including his body, his mind, his emotions, his spirit, and his wallet.\n\nSteve chose to share what he had learned. Anyone ready to grow can use these practices to reshape how they spend their days.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Finding your guiding purpose',
        text: 'A life that feels full begins with knowing your reason for living. What do you really want, and what higher purpose pulls at you? In a world where social media shows off other people\'s lifestyles, it is easy to lose your own direction and copy a stranger\'s path.\n\nOn his own search for meaning, Steve picked up habits that helped him understand what was inside, and several of them follow.\n\nFirst, make your life about more than you. Pour time and effort into yourself and into the people who matter. Show your partner, your friends, and your children that you value them by paying attention, lending support, and cheering their growth. Second, become a giver. Help others without expecting anything in return. Drop off groceries to a neighbor, listen to a coworker, or volunteer at a shelter. Third, stay curious about living. Many people dread retirement because they think life ends there, but it does not. Keep traveling, keep spending time with family, and keep learning something new. A bright outlook makes all the difference. Fourth, write a mission statement that captures your goals and dreams. Put it where you will see it every morning, like above the bathroom sink. Fifth, picture your future. Ask yourself where you want to be in thirty years. If the picture is fuzzy, start sharpening it. Build a vision board and hang it at home, or write a letter from your future self. Once you can see the destination, work backward and set goals for one month, one year, ten years, and twenty years.\n\nPicking a clear direction is the first step toward any meaningful change.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Health comes before money',
        text: 'When Steve was young, he admired his wealthy boss. He figured that anyone with that much money must be happy. But the more time they spent together, the more Steve saw the truth. The man was heavy and uncomfortable, and his poor health shaped every decision he made. He was so unhappy that he tried to spread that misery to the people around him. That is why your health has to come first. It is the only way to enjoy everything else you build.\n\nThe size of your bank account means nothing if you are too sick to leave the house.\n\nStaying healthy is not complicated, but it does take effort. Eating well means searching for recipes, learning new cooking methods, and steering clear of fast food even when you are tired after work. Exercise means reshaping your schedule, finding the right gear, and getting used to pushing through tough workouts.\n\nSteve\'s answer is to remove friction and turn healthy habits into something that feels fun and easy. Here are a few places to start.\n\nClear the junk from your kitchen. When the bad snacks are gone, you have no choice but to reach for something better, and over time, that becomes a habit you are glad to have. Fill up on vegetables and greens. When your plate is full of good food, there is little room left for sugar and grease. Look for smarter swaps. If you crave soda or candy, try a fruit smoothie or a fresh fruit bowl. Make movement fun. Put on music, listen to a podcast, or join a friend for a jog, a hike, or a bike ride.\n\nPick one small, clear goal each day, and let it pull you into a healthier rhythm.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Train your mind for strength',
        text: 'Your mind is the most powerful tool you have. When it is sharp and flexible, you can reach new heights, push through hard seasons, and build things that matter. A strong mindset is not something you are born with. It is something you grow over time, and the path is not always easy. A few short phrases can help you stay on track.\n\nLook for the bright side. This idea is old, but it works. Imagine you lose your job. On the surface, that feels terrible. You have to tighten your budget and hunt for work in a tough market. If you look for the lesson, though, you might notice that losing a job gives you a chance to start a fresh chapter and try paths you were afraid to walk before.\n\nAdopt a mindset of plenty. From time to time, you will see people who seem to have more than you, online or in real life. Do you compare yourself to them? Those comparisons only build walls between you and your goals. In truth, the world is full of chances for everyone, whether you are chasing money, recognition, or a sense of purpose.\n\nDecide even when you lack information. When a big choice shows up, return to your mission. Use your real goals as a guide, and the right path becomes clearer.\n\nKeep learning for life. The more you learn, the longer you stay useful, and the more doors open up. Try a new hobby to spark fresh thinking, or sign up for a class, a workshop, or a museum visit.\n\nIt is not the truth of who you are that holds you back. It is the deep belief that you are not enough.'
      },
      {
        title: 'You grow with the right people',
        text: 'Plants grow in sunlight, and people grow when they have strong relationships around them. Take a moment to look at your circle. Do you have someone you can tell anything to? Are there friends and family who lift your mood the moment they call? Do your relationships drain you, or do they fill you back up? People are the source of your emotional life, so choose your crowd with care.\n\nWatch out for friends who pull you into habits you do not want.\n\nIn his own life, Steve makes sure that the people close to him match a simple three-part test.\n\nThe first part is trust and loyalty. Trust is the grease that keeps life moving. You trust the taxi driver to take you where you want to go. You trust the chef to cook your food safely. In a close relationship, trust is the promise that you will not be hurt. To build it, keep your word and own your mistakes. If something feels off, talk it through calmly.\n\nThe second part is shared purpose. Trust alone is not enough. You also need to know that the other person sees life the way you do. Does this person push you forward and stir up your energy? Do their actions and goals line up with yours? If not, be careful about where the friendship might take you, and walk away if you need to.\n\nThe third part is simple fun. Life cannot all be serious. Plan trips, play small pranks, send memes, and start a few traditions of your own. Fun like this strengthens your bond and softens the hard moments.\n\nUse words that put you on the same team, like we instead of you.\n\nTogether, these three parts create a healthy space where family ties, friendships, and romances can grow strong.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Work smart, not just hard',
        text: 'The phrase follow your dreams sounds nice, but it will not pay your rent. Dreams cannot cover your bills, but discipline, determination, and careful spending can. So where do you start? You have probably heard that your money should work for you, which means investing in assets that grow in value. Before that, though, you have to earn it, and that is where your natural strengths come in.\n\nAsk yourself three questions. First, am I paid fairly for what I do, and should I ask for more? Second, what can I do to earn a raise? Third, should I start a side project on the side?\n\nIf you are already good at your job and you are hitting your goals, focus on the first question and ask for a raise. If you cannot justify one, it is time to raise your value in the market. Sign up for training, take on a hard project, or volunteer for a stretch assignment. Each step builds your skills and your leverage. A side project is another way to grow your income and use the talents you already have.\n\nDo not wait to be noticed. Step up and stand out on your own.\n\nOnce you have money to work with, you can start investing. Steve leans on a few guiding rules. Timing matters, because when the market drops, you can buy assets at a lower price and let time do the rest. Watch what you buy, and look for things that bring in steady cash without needing you to manage them every day, like real estate. Stay skeptical, and look closely at every deal for hidden problems.\n\nKeep an eye on this: your goal should be to earn back what you put in within three years. If you plan to sell within that window, the investment has to bring in serious profit.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'The word rich does not have to mean money. You can feel rich by tending to your spirit, your health, your closest relationships, and your love of learning. Money is only a tool, and the real wealth is the life you build with it.\n\nTry one of these ideas. Send a quick message to a friend or a family member just to say you are thinking of them. Chew each bite of food around thirty times and notice the flavors and textures, which also helps your stomach. Open a notebook and write when your feelings get heavy, even if the words feel messy. Push yourself with a challenge like 75 Hard, thirty days of coding, or thirty days of writing.\n\nDid you make it to the end?'
      }
    ]
  },
  'salt-fat-acid-heat.json': {
    base: { id: 'salt-fat-acid-heat', title: 'Salt, Fat, Acid, Heat', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781682213954 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'A simple formula for great cooking',
        text: 'Samin Nosrat has spent her life chasing flavor, and she found one secret that works with or without a recipe. The four pillars are salt, fat, acid, and heat. At first, they sound almost too simple, and they are. But Samin noticed that nobody was using this framework to teach cooking, so she decided to write the book herself.\n\nOnce you understand salt, fat, acid, and heat, the kitchen becomes ten times easier and far more fun.\n\nEvery choice in the kitchen rests on these four. Salt lifts the flavor. Fat carries it. Acid balances and brightens. Heat shapes the texture.\n\nWhen you master them, you can turn almost any set of ingredients into a great meal, even without a recipe in hand.\n\nCooking is open to anyone, and the result can be delicious.\n\nOnce you know the principles, you have more freedom in the kitchen. You stop being afraid to improvise, you start mixing what you already have, and you pick produce based on what looks and smells best, not what a recipe demands. You begin to trust your senses and your gut, and you adjust the recipe as you go.\n\nSamin\'s love for cooking started young. Food fascinated her as a child, and that love carried her to Italy, where she trained under Benedetta Vitali, a Tuscan chef with an eye for flavor. Over time, her belief in the power of salt, fat, acid, and heat grew, and it all poured out in this unusual cookbook.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Why salt is irreplaceable',
        text: 'Salt gets a rough reputation, but it is hard to replace in the kitchen. The body needs it too, because salt helps regulate blood pressure and the way water moves through your cells. Many people crave salty food, which is good news, because we cannot live without it.\n\nIn cooking, salt is the great amplifier. It boosts flavor and wakes up the smell of food. More salt does not always mean better food, though. Once you learn your salts and start tasting as you cook, your meals will never feel flat.\n\nSalt lifts a dish and brings out the best in the other ingredients.\n\nIt can feel tricky at first, because there are many kinds of salt, including table salt, kosher salt, Maldon, and fleur de sel, and you have to know how much to use and when. Samin recommends kosher salt for everyday cooking, since it has no additives and dissolves fast, and a finishing salt like fleur de sel for the top of a finished dish. Sea salt comes in larger grains and adds a nice crunch.\n\nWhen it comes to how much to use, tasting is the rule. Sample your food at every step of the recipe. Salt is not a one-time sprinkle. If a dish tastes dull, add a pinch and watch how the flavor changes. Do not panic about over-salting, because you can rescue a dish with water or a few extra neutral ingredients. Mistakes are part of learning.\n\nTiming matters too. You cannot wait until the pasta is on the plate and hope a final sprinkle will do the job. Some foods, like meat, need salt in advance so the flavor spreads and the texture softens. Seafood, though, can dry out if you salt it too early.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The power of fat in cooking',
        text: 'Like salt, fat has been given a bad name. Many people try to cut it out completely, but the truth is that we cannot live without it. Fat helps the body absorb vitamins, fuels key processes, and stores energy for later. Most of all, fat is at the heart of what makes food taste good.\n\nFat can play several roles in the kitchen.\n\nAs the main ingredient, fat shapes flavor and texture. Picture a burger with no fat, or a pastry dough with no butter. As a cooking medium, fat shines because it can take high heat and turn your ingredients golden and rich. As a finishing touch, fat lifts the flavor of a dish. A drizzle of olive oil on bruschetta turns a simple bite into something special.\n\nThere are far more kinds of fat than salt, from olive oil and butter to seed oils, nut oils, and animal fats, and each one has its place. When it comes to olive oil, there is no single best type for every dish. People\'s taste buds are different, and the good oils are not always easy to spot. What matters is knowing what you do not want, which is anything that tastes bitter, greasy, or off. Try a few kinds and find the one you like. Price is not always a sign of quality, so a great olive oil can come from your local shop at a fair price.\n\nTrying things out and learning from mistakes is how good food becomes memorable.\n\nHow do you use fat to make food shine? The first rule is layering, which means using more than one kind of fat in the same dish. Add melted butter to a waffle batter for flavor, then oil the waffle iron with the fat left from frying bacon. The second rule is balance. If a dish feels too heavy, add more ingredients or a splash of water. If it feels too dry, bring it back to life with a little olive oil, a spoon of sour cream, an egg yolk, or some grated cheese.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Acid for balance and brightness',
        text: 'People often call the best dishes mouthwatering, and that is exactly where acid comes in. Your mouth makes more saliva when you eat something sour, which helps protect your teeth. Acid is mostly about balance. Sour food on its own is not always a treat, but when you pair it with the right ingredients, it lights up the whole plate.\n\nThe basic sources of acid in the kitchen are vinegar, citrus, pickles, and dairy. Apple cider vinegar works well in salads, while rice vinegar shows up in many Asian dishes. For German red cabbage, reach for red wine vinegar. A squeeze of lemon takes hummus to another level. No good guacamole is complete without lime. Stay away from bottled lemon juice, because it tastes bitter and never matches the real thing.\n\nThink about the dish you want to make and where it comes from, then pick the acid that fits.\n\nIt is hard to find a vegetable that cannot be pickled, and even harder to find a meal that does not get better with a pickle on the side. Toss pickled carrots onto a steak, and it turns into a taco. Yogurt on a lamb kebab brings a bright, tangy note. Red wine and tomatoes can carry a lamb shoulder straight to Greece.\n\nAcid also makes food look more alive. Splash vinegar on a salad right before serving, and the colors seem to pop. Brush lemon juice on half an avocado, and the green stays fresh. Acid can change texture too, which is why you add wine to caramelized onions only after they have softened.\n\nCaramelization produces acid on its own. As sugar heats up, it breaks into many new compounds, and one of them is acid. That is why caramelized sugar in ice cream tastes more vivid than plain sugar.\n\nOnce again, the best way to learn what acid can do is to taste and experiment. Layering matters here too, so think about which acids you want to use and when to add them.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Heat as the great transformer',
        text: 'No other element changes food the way heat does. It is less obvious than salt, fat, or acid, so you have to use every sense you have, including touch, smell, sound, sight, taste, and good judgment. As you learn how food reacts to heat, you will start to use that power in all kinds of clever ways.\n\nThe key thing to remember is that the outside and the inside of the food should be ready at the same time. A burnt outside with a raw middle is just as sad as pale, mushy potatoes. Water is part of almost every food, and heat and water work together. If too much water boils off, the food dries out. If the heat stays gentle, the food stays moist and tender. Heat controls how much water your food keeps.\n\nFood has many parts, and you have to balance them all.\n\nWhen you freeze food, watch out for dehydration. At low temperatures, the water inside the cells expands and forms crystals, which can leave the food watery and bland. That is why a steak left in the freezer for three years will not make a good dinner. Like fat, water is also a medium. It softens hard vegetables and turns them tender. A gentle simmer in water is what makes a good custard.\n\nSteam is your clue for browning. As long as your onions are giving off steam, water is still leaving, and the browning will not start until the steam slows down. Keep the lid on if you want tender, soft food.\n\nCooking does not begin when you turn on the stove or preheat the oven. It begins with the temperature of the ingredients themselves. That starting temperature affects how fast and evenly the food cooks. A steak straight from the freezer will cook unevenly in the oven. The same idea applies to butter and dough. Pie dough needs cold butter for a crisp crust, while other recipes call for melted butter mixed in from the start.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Choosing what to cook',
        text: 'When it is time to pick a dish, Samin likes to use a trick she calls anchoring. Pick one central piece and build the meal around it. The anchor can be a single ingredient in the fridge, a cooking method you have been wanting to try, or even a limit, like time. You are not going to make cream soup without a blender, and you cannot bake an apple pie without an oven.\n\nAnchoring keeps the kitchen calm and the cooking organized.\n\nSometimes you crave the food of a specific place. If you want Mexican for dinner, think about the flavors that make it Mexican and choose your dish from there. Let your fridge and pantry lead the way. With the rules of salt, fat, acid, and heat, even a pack of pasta, a few onions, and some tomatoes can become a great dinner. It helps to know what you already have on hand, because building a meal is much easier when you know your ingredients.\n\nIf a dish is missing something, return to the lessons of salt, fat, and acid and check the balance.\n\nPick the freshest ingredients you can, because fresh food tastes the best. Trust your senses. A tomato that smells like nothing will taste like nothing. Wilted greens look the way they taste. Frozen fruits and vegetables are not a bad choice when fresh ones are not around, especially when they are cooked with care.\n\nAlways keep layering in mind. Light appetizers should come before heavy main courses. Play with textures for a richer eating experience, like tossing breadcrumbs on a soup for a little crunch. Match the food to the season so the ingredients feel right together. To keep your palate from wearing out, season one part of the meal boldly and keep the rest mild. Balance is everything.\n\nA garde-manger is the person in a restaurant kitchen who keeps track of the pantry and the fridge and makes sure the team knows what is in stock.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'Once you master the spirit of salt, fat, acid, and heat, you can turn almost any meal into something special. You will not learn all of the details in a single afternoon, though. Getting comfortable with these four elements takes practice, and practice means a few happy accidents along the way.\n\nTasting is your sharpest tool. Sample what you are cooking, and adjust the elements until the flavor feels right. Keep the core jobs in mind. Salt lifts the flavor, fat carries it, acid brightens it, and heat transforms the food.\n\nSalt, fat, and acid come in many varieties, and each one has its own personality. Samin shares her favorite pairings, like using sea salt as a finishing touch, but she also encourages you to play and invent your own. Timing is just as important as the ingredients themselves. Salt added at the wrong moment cannot save a pot of pasta. An oven that was not preheated will never bake a good batch of cookies.\n\nUse anchoring and layering in your cooking. Picking a central element to build around makes the whole process feel more organized. Think about the ingredients you have, the limits you face, your mood, and what you are hungry for. Then look for combinations that bring out the best in those ingredients, both by contrast and by harmony.\n\nTry this\n\nPick a dish you love but have never made yourself. Break it down in terms of salt, fat, acid, and heat. What gives it that special flavor? Be brave, and try cooking it from scratch.\n\nDid you make it to the end?'
      }
    ]
  },
  'salt-sugar-and-fat-how-the-food-giants-hooked-us.json': {
    base: { id: 'salt-sugar-and-fat-how-the-food-giants-hooked-us', title: 'Salt, Sugar and Fat', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781682309371 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'How processed food took over the kitchen',
        text: 'Home-cooked meals used to be the rule, but in recent years the food industry has flooded the market with heavily processed products. What makes a meal appealing comes down to many things, including sweet, sour, spicy, and other flavors the taste buds can pick up. Research has shown that sweetness is the one flavor we notice more than any other.\n\nWe pick up sweetness more than any other flavor, so we are built to crave sweet dishes and snacks. Our sweet tooth is not really a tooth, by the way. It is our tongue, parts of the roof of our mouth, and even parts of the stomach that do the sensing. That fact is not new to the big food companies that sell us processed food.\n\nNever underestimate how much sugar is hiding in what you eat.\n\nOnce the food companies knew this, they began loading their products with extra sugar and other additives for the rest of us.\n\nIn the 1950s, television had just arrived, and more women were starting jobs that left them less time to cook. The timing was perfect for the food industry. Catchy commercials and products designed to wake up the sweet tooth brought in a growing customer base. These new, "convenient" foods were not enough to push home cooking aside, though, mostly because home economics teachers were still teaching kids how to cook.\n\nNo matter how long it takes to prepare, home-cooked food is usually the better choice.\n\nThere was no need to rely on processed food when kids could cook for themselves. The fix was to bring home economics teachers on board and have them endorse processed meals as the better option. It worked almost overnight. Support poured in, and home cooking lost ground, thanks to the sugar, fat, and salt baked into these new products. That is a quick history lesson. In the chapters ahead, we will dig into the food industry, see its tricks, and learn how you can protect yourself from unhealthy eating.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Sugar is everywhere in processed food',
        text: 'Back when humans were just starting to climb the food chain, we craved sugary food in large amounts. Not necessarily sweet candy, but anything with sugars that the body could turn into energy. Fruits and starchy foods carry plenty of sugar and gave early humans the fuel to run from predators or to fight them off.\n\nIt is no longer wise to load up on sugary food, because too much can lead to serious health problems. We may want sugar all the time, but our bodies have a built-in ceiling for how much we can handle. Even if we cannot stop ourselves, there is a point where we really cannot take more. The processed food companies, of course, know this useful fact.\n\nWe have to learn to tame our craving for sugary food to avoid health trouble.\n\nNot every company pays attention to that ceiling. In fact, many of them choose to ignore it and pile on as much sugar as they can. Most people do not realize how much sugar is hiding in the processed food and drinks they consume, which is exactly what makes them reach for more. The average American eats around 22 teaspoons of sugar a day, and more than 70 percent of that comes from processed food alone.\n\nWe eat these products without thinking about our health because they taste good, and we slowly damage our bodies. The damage does not stop at products that list sugar on the label, either. Plenty of foods do not need sugar but have it added anyway, so even a plain bowl of pasta can come with extra sugar.\n\nTasty or not, processed meals are best avoided.\n\nPasta sauce is one example. After tomatoes, the main ingredient is often sugar. These pairings are odd and unfair, because sugar has no business being in a savory dish.\n\nIf sugar is the stimulant of the processed food world, hitting the brain fast and hard, then fat is the slow operator, sliding in quietly with a powerful effect of its own.\n\nThe average can of tomato paste carries at least 12 grams of sugar, which is around six sugar cubes.'
      },
      {
        title: 'People kept eating the same harmful food',
        text: 'By the 1970s, it was becoming clear that the steady rise in sugar and processed food was doing real damage to public health, and yet people kept buying the same products.\n\nThe boom in sweet food led to a sharp jump in cavities among children. Looking closer, researchers found an unsettling pattern driven by the most powerful ad tool of the era, the television. Kids were watching commercials for sweet breakfast cereals, and later studies showed that those cereals were loaded with sugar, which fed the rise in childhood cavities. Sugar brought other health risks too, including a higher chance of diabetes. While children dealt with their teeth, adults were facing life-threatening complications from the same disease. Throughout the 1970s, Americans were buried under a wave of illness that traced back to processed food and quick meals.\n\nIt is wise to be skeptical of what you see on TV, because those foods may look good but are not good for you.\n\nStrangely, none of this slowed the demand. Even as people learned that the food was harming them, they kept buying the well-packaged products that were making them sick.\n\nCutting back on sugar is the kindest thing you can do for your health.\n\nIn the 1980s, the public conversation about processed food got louder, but the sales kept climbing. Coca-Cola and other giants posted steady profit growth for decades, and by the end of the 1990s the average American was dealing with obesity, diabetes, and heart disease in large numbers.\n\nThat is how the sweetened breakfast was born, along with a core industry trick: swap out the problem ingredient for another one that the public is not yet worried about.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Fat is just as dangerous as sugar',
        text: 'Sugar is the first of the three big troublemakers in the food industry, and it is plenty powerful on its own, but fat is in a league of its own. We are wired to crave sugar and anything that tastes like it. Processed food companies know this, so they pour extra sugar into their products and reap the rewards.\n\nHere is the catch. To do real damage, sugar has to be added in large amounts, but the sugar in processed food only accounts for about half the calories that fat would in the same space. Gram for gram, fat has roughly twice the calories of sugar. That is a lot of extra calories, especially when we cannot taste when fat is too much.\n\nWatching for sugar matters, but watching for fat matters just as much.\n\nOur bodies have a built-in stop sign for sugar, so at least there is a natural brake. Fat has no such brake. We cannot taste it when it sits next to sugar, and we cannot tell when we have had too much. That gap is what lets processed food companies load their products with fat and still get away with it. The result is that the average American blows past the daily fat limit by about 50 percent, and obesity is the predictable outcome. Sugar and fat work as a team to keep us reaching for more. Fat helps products last longer on the shelf, which gives us more time to buy them, and sugar keeps us coming back for another bite.\n\nProcessed food is full of fat that helps it sit on the shelf, but that same fat is hard on your heart, so fresh food is the better pick.\n\nThe risks of all that fat and the calories that come with it should be obvious, but the line from fat to heart disease and type 2 diabetes is a straight one. The body can only burn through so many calories when we are sitting still.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Some "healthy" foods are not healthy at all',
        text: 'We know the basic food groups and the nutrients they provide, so we should be able to tell what to eat and what to skip. If that is true, then why do people who seem to eat well still put on extra weight and end up in the same shape as those who eat junk?\n\nTwo foods are at the center of that puzzle, milk and cheese. Cheese is already high in fat from the start, and processed cheese has even more. Two-thirds of the calories in cheese come from fat. The way cheese is made helps explain the heavy fat content.\n\nFat is a real danger, and cheese is loaded with it, so it is wise to cut back.\n\nIn the 1950s, demand for milk was growing, and the government wanted to keep milk affordable. They paid farmers a subsidy to keep production high, and the price stayed low. With so much milk on the market, health-conscious shoppers started asking for low-fat dairy. That was easy to arrange, but it left producers with a new problem. Where should all the skimmed milk fat go?\n\nSince the government was paying for the milk and every product that came with it, the farmers decided to turn the extra fat into cheese and sell it to shoppers. This "cheese" was full of saturated fat, which was exactly what people were trying to avoid, but they happily ate it anyway, and cheese consumption climbed.\n\nWhen the government tried to bring sugar levels down, consumers pushed back and asked for the old recipes. With cheese, the government kept funding the single biggest threat to public health, and most people did not even notice.\n\nRegulators do their best, but you have to take responsibility for what you put in your body.\n\nOnce again, most people ate whatever was on the shelf without checking. Studies show that cheese consumption in America has roughly tripled since 1970.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Salt is the third hidden danger',
        text: 'Salt often gets ignored because it does not carry the same calorie load as sugar and fat. It will not pile up as body fat, but it is not harmless either. The body needs a small amount of sodium for important functions, and salt is the main way we get it.\n\nToo much sodium in the blood makes the blood thinner and pushes it through the body faster. That change can grow into a much more serious problem called hypertension. This information was not widely known in earlier decades, so salt use climbed without anyone realizing the cost. By the 1980s, one in four Americans had hypertension.\n\nSodium is fine in small amounts, but salt intake has to be kept in check to prevent hypertension.\n\nThe early numbers were fuzzy, but research eventually pointed straight at salt. The average American eats 10 to 20 times more salt than the body needs in a day. That level of excess was hard to ignore, and the government stepped in to regulate the amount of salt in packaged food.\n\nThe real culprit, though, was processed food. The average canned or packaged meal often contains at least twice the safe daily limit of salt. That sounds extreme, but the food companies were not trying to poison anyone. So why was there so much salt?\n\nOne guess is that food tastes better with salt, so the more, the better. That is part of the story, but it does not explain the full amount. The bigger reason is the same as for fat, which is shelf life. Salt helps products sit on the shelf for longer, which means more sales, and the cost is paid by the people who eat them.\n\nSalt is easy to overlook, and that is exactly why processed food and salty snacks are best kept off the menu.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'It is so easy to pop a pre-made meal into the microwave and have dinner ready in a few minutes, the original meaning of fast food. That promise was the lure, but the food came loaded with more than catchy ads. It came packed with three of the most powerful ingredients in the modern diet, sugar, salt, and fat. Most people had no idea of the harm, and they kept eating until the consequences showed up in the form of obesity and disease.\n\nStudies show that many of the things we eat contain enough of these three ingredients to cover the daily needs of four or five adults. Consumers are often unaware of the risks they take with every bite. Even when regulators asked the food companies to cut back on sugar, fat, and salt, the public pushed back and asked for the old recipes. Our bodies are wired to want more of these ingredients, which is a kind of built-in sabotage. The good news is that we know far more about this today, and that knowledge can help people take better care of themselves.\n\nThe idea that some foods act like drugs on the brain goes back about twenty years in the scientific world.\n\nTry this\n\nWatch out for your own health, because the food companies are watching out for their profits. Take responsibility for what you eat, and you stand a much better chance of staying well.\n\nDid you make it to the end?'
      }
    ]
  },
  'sane-new-world.json': {
    base: { id: 'sane-new-world', title: 'Sane New World', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781608259698 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Depression is common, and you can recover',
        text: 'Many people in the world today do not even know they are living with depression. The world runs on pressure and busyness, and that pressure makes life harder than it has to be. People chase money, fame, and success so hard that they rarely stop to take a real breath.\n\nIn trying to keep up with the endless demands, people try to do many things at once, and that kind of multitasking has driven most of them close to breaking point. Even computers crash when you ask them to do too much.\n\nThe 21st century is a lot. It moves fast, demands a great deal, and carries a steady hum of fear. Keeping up with it is hard, and that leaves little room to figure out what really matters. Many people walk through their days feeling worn out, but it does not have to stay that way.\n\nThis summary is meant to help anyone take charge of their mind. The chapters ahead will help you get to know yourself better, and with practice, you can learn to manage your own thoughts.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Why the feeling of emptiness drives us',
        text: 'Humans are their own worst taskmasters. We carry a built-in engine that pushes us to achieve and keep moving. Everyone has a kind of selfish gene, the leading force that drives each person to press on. Parents add to that pressure, too. Every complaint and correction sticks in a child\'s mind. These voices can wear a person down, but they can also help them push through obstacles.\n\nA lot of people put on a show of being busy and important. They do it to cover up the inner feeling of being useless, so they run from one task to the next. They run because they do not want to stop and look at the emptiness inside.\n\nEvolution has shaped our brain to help the body survive and reproduce, not to chase happiness, and the brain has plenty on its plate.\n\nMany people act busier than they really are. Society worships busyness, so everyone tries to play the part.\n\nSome people try to find love and approval through shopping, buying things they do not really need.\n\nClothing, designer or not, is a way of showing who you are. Another big marker is the answer to the question, what do you do? People carry their identity on business cards, and new job titles keep popping up to label abstract roles.\n\nEach person believes they have a purpose somewhere inside, but most of the time that belief is a kind of wishful thinking. In truth, most people still have a long emotional road to walk.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Unmet desires keep us from seeing our blessings',
        text: 'A few emotional shortfalls are common to many people, and they are worth knowing.\n\nEnvy is one. Sometimes people want what they do not really need. Whatever it is, they want it, and they may even wish harm on the person who has it.\n\nRage is another. Anger is widespread in the human mind. A calm person can turn into an unrecognizable fury in a flash.\n\nDeception is part of being human. People know how to bend situations in their favor. A person who wants to block someone else can wreck a job offer, a relationship, or a deal, and humans are animals under the skin, doing whatever it takes to get by.\n\nFacial expressions can also fool those around us. Evolution gave people a range of expressions to throw others off the scent. People laugh even when they are nowhere close to happy.\n\nJealousy is not just a kid\'s feeling. Adults feel it just as strongly, even when they keep it hidden.\n\nPeople\'s wants run a wide range, from basic needs like food, water, and shelter all the way to a private jet with a hot tub. The failure to get what we want leaves us stuck in a loop of longing.\n\nHumans are given the basics for life, like breath, sight, hearing, and a mouth to talk and eat. Even with all that, many people suffer, and the cause is usually negative thinking.\n\nEven when they are not chasing the next thing, humans spend a lot of time waiting for what is about to happen.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Mental illness is real and does not pick its victims',
        text: 'Depression can sound exaggerated, but it is a real problem. Many people are at the mercy of their own strong feelings, and that is often how depression takes hold. Depression does not care whether you are famous, live in a hut, or come from any culture. It can land on anyone.\n\nDepression is not sneaky, either. The signs are usually there to see, in the eyes of the person who is suffering, but it takes a careful look to spot them. For that reason, teachers should be trained to watch for early signs in students and to get them help before things get worse.\n\nThe way a person sees the world comes from what the brain is doing. The brain and the mind, including moods, emotions, thoughts, memories, and personality, are deeply linked. Depression is what happens when something goes wrong in the brain. Other brain-related conditions like prosopagnosia, Capgras syndrome, synesthesia, somatoparaphrenia, and Cotard\'s syndrome also come from brain trouble. Sadly, depression is often brushed aside.\n\nA lot of people do not know that depression shares the same brain circuits and symptoms as many other conditions. Most of these conditions are seen as neurological glitches that change the way a person acts, which is why the stigma around mental illness is unfair.\n\nMental illness can be set off by genes, by disease, by trauma, or even by a physical injury.\n\nDepression deserves to be taken seriously. Therapy and medicine help, but a big part of the cure is knowing that you are not alone. A person with depression needs to understand that they are sick in the same way people are sick with a physical illness.\n\nIt is common for people to think of a depressed person as self-indulgent, self-obsessed, or just looking for pity or an excuse to avoid responsibility. Loved ones may want to help, but they cannot really understand what it feels like. The best support often comes from people who have been through the same kind of struggle, because they are the only ones who truly know what depression feels like.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The brain shapes everything we do',
        text: 'The way our neurons, or brain cells, are wired together shapes the way we think. Everything a person can do, including dreams, hopes, fantasies, and fears, comes from the connections between neurons, the chemicals they release, and the specialized regions of the brain. Those neurons, chemicals, and regions are tuned by a person\'s genes, by the way they grew up, by the society they were born into, and by the influence of their parents.\n\nEvery thought, feeling, and perception leaves a mark on the brain, and those marks are how we learn. The brain is not just a pile of undifferentiated processors, though. It has regions that do specific jobs. Neurons fire off chemicals called neurotransmitters, and those chemicals form pathways and networks that carry out specialized functions. Those pathways allow the different brain regions to talk to one another.\n\nOur genetic code, written in DNA, tells every cell in the body what to do.\n\nAlong with neurons, genes play a major part in shaping who we are. No one knows exactly how much credit genes deserve, and it is not clear how much environment adds on top, but the two together decide the kind of person we become.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Nobody sees the world as it really is',
        text: 'A lot of people think they see the world exactly the way it is. Nobody likes to admit that the picture in their head is a little warped, but it is true.\n\nHumans live in a kind of virtual reality, because the world is not actually what we see.\n\nThink of the visual cortex in your brain as a projection room that builds up what is out there from the signals it receives. In reality, you see the world in a series of snapshots, and it is your brain that ties them together to feel like smooth motion.\n\nAround 70 different areas of the brain work together to build one picture of the world. Different parts handle color, movement, edges, shapes, and shadows. No single part of the brain gets the whole picture. In other brain regions, those images get a name, an association, or an emotional tag.\n\nNobody gets a full view of the world. All we get are small clips that drift through our awareness, and while we focus on one, a trillion other things are happening without us noticing.\n\nThe brain keeps the human heart beating over 100,000 times a day, pushing about two gallons of blood a minute through a network of blood vessels that stretches around 60,000 miles.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Stress is harmful to both body and mind',
        text: 'When the body feels stress, a chain of reactions kicks off. The thalamus, the brain\'s relay station, sends a wake-up call to the brain stem. From there, signals go out to the major organs and muscle groups, getting them ready to fight or run. The adrenal glands release stress hormones.\n\nCortisol lowers the immune system\'s response to keep swelling down after any injury, and it fires up the amygdala so you stay alert. That boost in alertness creates more cortisol in a feedback loop. Cortisol also slows the hippocampus, which reduces memory so you focus on what you did the last time you faced a similar threat. It also shuts down digestion and lowers sex drive, since thinking about food or intimacy during a crisis would only get in the way.\n\nEpinephrine, another chemical, makes the heart beat faster, moves more blood, and dilates the pupils, sometimes leaving you feeling light-headed.\n\nAll of that chemistry is useful if you are truly in danger. If you are not in a life-or-death moment and those chemicals keep flowing, they start to damage the body and brain. They can kill off neurons in the hippocampus, which leads to lasting memory loss.\n\nOxygen and blood are sent out to the arms and legs to get them ready for action, but if they stay there too long, the brain runs low on air and fresh blood, and clear thinking falls apart. In the worst cases, the result is a coma, and it can be even worse than that.\n\nOver time, the excess chemicals wear down the immune system, leaving you open to viruses of every kind. They also lower serotonin, which leaves you joyless and pulls you into depression.\n\nIf the chemical storm keeps going, it can lead to heart disease, hardened arteries, type 2 diabetes, and certain cancers.\n\nStress, along with the chemicals it sets loose, will quietly break you down mentally and physically. The good news is that you can learn to manage these chemicals, boosting the ones that help you and lowering the ones that hurt you.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Mindfulness sharpens the mind and lifts depression',
        text: 'With mindful practice, you can learn to take the reins of your mind and guide it where you want it to go.\n\nMindfulness is not complicated. All you have to do is pay attention. When you focus on what is happening right now, you begin to notice that thoughts are not facts. They are patterns that come and go, change, scatter, and fade.\n\nThe point of mindfulness is to teach yourself that thoughts are your servant, not your master.\n\nA few simple exercises can help you get the hang of taming your mind.\n\nThe first is called RAIN. It stands for Recognize, Accept, Investigate, and Non-identification. Start by recognizing the feeling, whether it is fear, anger, or sadness. The next step is to let go of blame and shame. Then, send your attention to where the feeling sits in your body. Is your chest tight, or is there a churn in your stomach? Once you have noticed that, the next step is to step back from the feeling. That distance helps you regulate yourself. You will not snap out of sadness in a moment, but you will give yourself room to explore it.\n\nThe second exercise is called stop and notice. It only takes five seconds. The idea is to pause in the middle of a task and observe your mind and body. Notice what is going on inside, then carry on. Try this at the start of small activities like brushing your teeth, taking a shower, taking out the trash, or doing the laundry.\n\nThe third exercise is to focus on your feet. Sit or stand with your feet on the floor, your spine straight but not stiff. You can close your eyes or lower your gaze. Pay attention to the feeling of the ground under you. Notice the weight, the temperature, the tingling, or the lack of any feeling at all. When your mind wanders, take note of where it went and bring your attention back to your feet.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'Life is full of uncertainty, and there is very little that anyone can truly control. Holding on tight to anything is pointless, because it only causes more pain.\n\nTo survive, the brain tricks you into believing the world is full of fixed patterns and that people can lay down permanent plans. The brain is always chasing past moments and trying to manage them, but that does not really work. It is better to learn to manage your own thoughts instead.\n\nIf your thoughts are running the show, they will slowly squeeze you with bitterness. You will become harder, more judgmental, and less tolerant, and the world will feel smaller and duller.\n\nYou have the power to manage your attention and build a path toward health and happiness. All it takes is lowering your reactive habits and growing more positive emotions.\n\nBroadening the way people see themselves and the world should be the next stage of human growth. Doing so will widen human awareness and expand the choices people have, because they will be able to pick the right path before they act. People can grow wiser, make choices that pay off in the long run, and take action that benefits the future.\n\nPutting mindfulness into practice will do a lot of good for everyone. It can affect inequality, the climate crisis, poverty, and disease. Mindfulness can help build a world where it is not the strongest who survive, but the wisest.\n\nTry this\n\nSurprise yourself and break a habit. Each small change in habit chips away at the wall you have built around yourself. Before long, you will be able to break out of the prison you made.\n\nDid you make it to the end?'
      }
    ]
  },
  'scaling-up.json': {
    base: { id: 'scaling-up', title: 'Scaling Up', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781637195784 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Scaling up boosts productivity in any company',
        text: 'For most entrepreneurs, growing a business feels like a leap they would rather not take. Scaling up means change, and change pulls people away from the routines they already know. That is why so few companies manage to pull it off. A few common barriers show up again and again. Leadership can hold a company back when there are not enough leaders willing to delegate. Infrastructure becomes a problem when the systems and resources cannot keep up with the decisions that come with growth. Marketing turns into a hurdle when the company cannot build a real function that pulls in new buyers.\n\nTo clear these hurdles, a company has to set rules that everyone follows, and those rules should become the company\'s core values. Next comes a strategy that puts the customer first and sets the business apart from the competition. Breaking big jobs into smaller pieces using a WWW approach, which stands for Who, What, When, makes execution easier and helps with management, communication, and accountability. Cash management is the final piece, and it keeps the plan moving on schedule.\n\nScaling up is not easy, and problems will pop up along the way. A solid strategy is the best way to deal with those problems early and to put the business in a stronger place.\n\nIf a company is making less profit than it should, it is time to think about scaling up.\n\nThis summary will break down what it means to scale up a business. It will also show how core values and clear boundaries help a company grow.\n\nLetting go of control and trusting others to do good work is one of the hardest parts of leading a growing organization.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A company needs the right people on the bus',
        text: 'The people around a leader matter when it is time to scale up. People inside the company and outside it, including investors, customers, and suppliers, all play a part in the outcome. There are two questions that every business leader should ask if they want their company to grow. First, am I happy, and are there partners or investors making my life harder than it needs to be? Second, would I enthusiastically rehire every person on my team, knowing what I know today?\n\nAnswering these questions honestly can save a leader a lot of emotional drain. Business owners should pay close attention to how they attract and hire their staff. Anyone can put a person in a seat, but not everyone can put the right person there. Leaders cannot afford to copy what the competition does, so the hiring process and the strategy behind it have to be their own. Hire people who share the company\'s values and who believe in them.\n\nClear values and a clear purpose help a company pull in the right people.\n\nSometimes business owners have to put extra energy into finding the right hires, because the larger a company gets, the more careful it has to be about who comes on board. A company that does not split its team into the right roles, that does not give authority where it is due, and that does not hold leaders accountable will eventually fall apart. It is a lot like a cell. A cell grows until it has to divide, and if it tries to keep growing without dividing, it cannot take in enough nutrients or get rid of waste, and it dies from within.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Good management keeps the team happy and engaged',
        text: 'One of the biggest obstacles to growth is the lack of strong managerial leadership. Managers in a growing company have five main jobs to do. They hire fewer people but pay them well. They recognize people and show appreciation. They set clear expectations and give each employee a clear line of sight. They stop demotivating and start dehassling, which means clearing the unnecessary friction. They help people play to their strengths.\n\nHiring fewer people and paying them more is a smart way to start. Hire one strong person instead of three, train them well, and pay them more than the average competitor. That step alone can do a lot for the company\'s growth.\n\nRecognition and appreciation mean a lot to people, especially when it comes from a manager. Feeling seen helps a company keep its best performers. It is one habit that every manager should build into the workweek.\n\nGreat managers care about the differences between their team members and how those differences affect the work.\n\nClear expectations and a clear line of sight help every team member see where the company is going and how their work fits in. Managers should make sure that the daily, weekly, and quarterly targets line up with the bigger picture.\n\nStop demotivating and start dehassling. Every manager has to keep an eye on what kills motivation, knowing that the right answer changes from team to team. That may mean letting someone go, hiring a new face, or cutting processes that slow people down. The goal is the same, which is to give the team the best working environment possible.\n\nHelp people play to their strengths. A good manager knows what gives each person energy and what drains them, and they hand out work based on that knowledge. A great manager can describe each team member\'s strengths, personality, and recent wins in detail.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A strong core is the foundation of good strategy',
        text: 'Scaling up depends on having a clear, original strategy that delivers on the company\'s promises. Core values are the rules and boundaries that shape a company\'s culture and personality, and they guide the behavior and decisions of everyone who works there. Managers have to lead by example, making sure that how they live lines up with the company\'s values. When the values are clear, the company runs smoothly, and employees know the right thing to do when a hard call comes their way.\n\nCore values, purpose, competencies, and strategy are the pieces that build a vision worth scaling up.\n\nCore competencies make the strategy sharper and make the company easier to work with. The core purpose sits at the heart of the company. It is why an employee chooses to work there, and it is why a customer chooses to buy. The purpose should come from a sincere place and should reach beyond just making money. The core competencies set the edges of what a company does well, and they help managers and employees understand how to use their skills.\n\nIf the core values are the soul of the organization, the core purpose gives it heart.\n\nWhen it comes to strategy planning, having everyone on the same page makes everything easier. Everyone should know what strategy the company is following, and the strategy itself should be as simple as possible.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A great idea still has to be executed',
        text: 'Putting a strategy into action takes more than a good plan. Every business leader should pay attention to three things, including priorities, data, and meeting rhythms.\n\nPriorities are the first piece. Business managers should pick the most important, measurable focus for each quarter. A company with too many priorities often ends up achieving none of them. Sticking to a single priority per quarter, for example one big goal at a time, makes the company stronger and gives everyone a clear target to support.\n\nA healthy team is one where every voice is heard and considered.\n\nData is the second piece. Effective execution depends on gathering data from stakeholders and customers. Speed matters here, and gathering data on a regular schedule, for as long as possible, makes the process easier. The company uses the data as feedback to guide decisions. Management can use that feedback to bring employees into the conversation about specific products and choices. This loop tightens the link between employees and management. Gathering the data is only part of the work, though. Analyzing it, collecting feedback, and understanding how the data affects customers and products is what closes the loop.\n\nMeeting rhythm is the third piece. After setting priorities and gathering data, the next step is to build a steady meeting rhythm. Regular meetings, including daily, monthly, quarterly, and annual gatherings, help the company handle communication and reach its goals. They also give the team a chance to talk through the most important issues facing the business.\n\nTo get good at execution, leaders have to listen to their customers and employees, gather data, hold regular meetings to discuss the data, and set priorities based on what they find.\n\nGoals without routines are just wishes, and routines without goals wander in circles. The best business leaders have a clear vision and the disciplines, or routines, to make it real.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A thriving business needs healthy cash flow',
        text: 'Scaling up costs real money. At this stage, business owners need to find ways to bring in profit and cash flow on their own, instead of leaning on loans. That kind of growth takes careful work and a clear sense of the company\'s cash conversion cycle, which is the time it takes for the company to spend cash and then take that same cash back in. The shorter the cycle, the more money the company makes. To run the cycle well, the company has to know how much it earns each day, why some customers pay late, and how to set up the right rewards for the team.\n\nSpeeding up every part of the cycle helps the cash come in faster. When products ship quickly, customers can buy sooner. Cutting mistakes out of the process makes customers more willing to pay on time, because nobody likes dealing with errors.\n\nEvery step in the right direction adds up to the company\'s core success.\n\nCash is only part of the picture. The accounting process matters just as much. Good accounting helps the company make smarter financial decisions and spot trends. Accounting is not only for tax time. It tracks cash flow, builds the financial data the company needs, and helps with forecasting and debt management. For example, Harnish told the story of a company that hired Greg Crabtree\'s accounting team after losing money for 14 years, even with five million dollars in revenue. Within five years, the company had grown to twenty-five million in revenue, the owner was debt free, and the business was generating real after-tax income.\n\nAccording to the Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development, around 57 percent of leaders have been through a moment when they feared their business might fail.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'In scaling up a company, everything counts, from the kind of people the company hires to the strategy it picks and the way it manages cash. Everyone in the company has to know the core values and the role they play in the long game. Leaders have to bring in the right people, people who are excited about scaling up.\n\nManagers need to be plugged into what is happening at every stage of growth. That does not mean doing all the work themselves, but it does mean staying aware. If the company is growing, remember that cash flow is just as important as profit. That is how companies like Amazon keep growing even when they report a loss. In 2013, Amazon\'s business model brought in around three billion dollars in cash flow, which fueled real growth even in a year of reported losses.\n\nManagement should make sure every quarter has a clear goal and that the team is moving toward it. A weekly leadership council can set the company\'s priorities and pick a theme for the quarter. Routines are a great way to set a standard for both leaders and employees, because they keep everyone aligned on the company\'s goals and the strategies that will get them there. No single playbook fits every company, but it is always possible to try today, try again tomorrow, and take it one step at a time.\n\nTry this\n\nBuild a monthly, weekly, and daily routine of touchpoints for the management team and the rest of the staff to talk through how to grow the company. For example, hold a five to fifteen minute meeting each day to cover the most important issues and quick updates, and move anything bigger to the weekly meeting.\n\nDid you make it to the end?'
      }
    ]
  }
};
